The '''Hume-Rothery rules''', named after [[William Hume-Rothery]], are a set of basic rules that describe the conditions under which an element could dissolve in a [[metal]], forming a [[solid solution]]. There are two sets of rules; one refers to substitutional solid solutions, and the other refers to [[Interstitial defect|interstitial]] solid solutions.
==Substitutional solid solution rules== For substitutional solid solutions, the Hume-Rothery rules are as follows:
# The [[atomic radius]] of the solute and [[solvent]] atoms must differ by no more than 15%: #:<math> \% \mbox{ difference} = \left ( \frac{r_{solute} - r_{solvent}}{r_{solvent}} \right ) \times 100\% \le 15\%.</math> # The [[crystal structure]]s of solute and solvent must be similar. # Complete [[solubility]] occurs when the solvent and solute have the same [[Valence (chemistry)|valency]].<ref>''Foundations of Materials Science and Engineering'', 4th ed., W. Smith and J. Hashemi, pp.139-140 (2006).</ref> A metal of higher valency is more likely to dissolve in a metal with lower valency.<ref>VALENCY EFFECTS AND RELATIVE SOLUBILITIES IN TRANSITION METAL ALLOYS D. A. Goodman* and L. H. Bennett National Bureau of Standards, Washington DC, 20234 R. E. Watson Brookhaven National Laboratory. </ref>{{citation needed | reason = Sources contradict each other. It appears more easily-obtainable 2ndary sources say lower is likelier to dissolve in higher than this. Two independent 2ndary sources are needed to leave this statement as is. References in talk page.|date=January 2018}} # The solute and solvent should have similar [[electronegativity]]. If the electronegativity difference is too great, the metals tend to form [[Intermetallics|intermetallic compounds]] instead of solid solutions.
==Interstitial solid solution rules== For [[Interstitial defect|interstitial]] solid solutions, the Hume-Rothery rules are:
# Solute atoms should have radius no larger than 59% of the radius of solvent atoms.<ref>https://madeeasy.in/admin/ESEGroup/12.%20ME_ESE_FST_Paper-2_Conv_2109.pdf</ref><ref>http://slideplayer.com/slide/7666224/</ref><ref>http://slideplayer.com/slide/5866092/</ref> # The solute and solvent should have similar [[electronegativity]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | title = Hume-Rothery Rules | encyclopedia = Van Nostrand's Scientific Encyclopedia | publisher = John Wiley & Sons, Inc | year = 2002 }}</ref> # They should show a wide range of composition.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} {{confusing | section | reason = this statement is either circular, or contradictory, or incomprehensible. |date=January 2018}} # Valency factor: two elements should have the same valence. The greater the difference in valence between solute and solvent atoms, the lower the solubility.
==See also== * [[CALPHAD]] * [[Enthalpy of mixing]] * [[Gibbs energy]] * [[Intermetallic]] compound * [[Phase diagram]] ==Notes== {{reflist}}
